dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Aizen & Escurra. 1998. High incidence of plant-animal mutualisms in the woody flora of the temperate forest of southern South America: biogeographical origin and present ecological significance. Ecologia Austral, 8, 217-236
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Find clues to the present pattern of high dependence on animals for pollination and dispersal by the woody flora of the temperate forest of suthern South America
Type_of_Analyses: We assessed pairwise associations between biogeographical affiliation, growth form, and mutualism-dependency by using G-tests. We used one-way ANOVAs to evaluate possible effects of presumed biogeographical origin (all seven categories), growth form (all five categories), and pollinator- and dispersar-dependency (three and two categories, respectively) on the southern latitudinal limit of genera.
Comments: Review article, plants not pollinated by S. sephaniodes are insect pollinated, but insect species not specified.

dwc:reference: Amico et al. 2007. Phylogenetic relationships and ecological speciation in the mistletoe Tristerix (Loranthaceae): the influence of pollinators, dispersers, and hosts. American Journal of Botany, 9(4), 558-567. doi: 10.3732/ajb.94.4.558
dwc:verbatimSite: Near Fray Jorge National Park, IV Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: The objective of the present study is to test the subgeneric classification of Tristerix by reconstructing the phylogeny of the genus using molecular markers—the first phylogeny for any genus in Loranthaceae. Moreover, we will use the molecular phylogeny to address the distribution of various morphological characters and life history features, particularly with respect to how abiotic and biotic factors have influenced speciation in the genus.
Type_of_Analyses: Individuals from different populations were used to test for monophyly in seven species. DNA was extracted from silica-dried leaf or flower tissue or in some cases herbarium samples. One-tenth dilutions of the genomic DNA were used for PCR amplifications for the three gene partitions. Individual sequences were aligned manually using BioEdit (Hall, 1999). PAUP* (Swofford, 2002) was used to conduct maximum parsimony (MP) analyses.

Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We addressed the following questions: (1) What is the functional structure of the flowers? (2) Are there floral visitors? (3) Are the taxa self-compatible? (4) Are self-pollination and autogamy possible, and if so, is self or cross-pollination the dominant mode? And (5) what is the implication of these data for the future conservation of these native species?
Type_of_Analyses: Descriptive study. Detailed description of floral structures for the taxa, as well as an analysis of floral funciton. Pollen quantity was estimated, and ovules were counted, P/O ratio estimated.

dwc:verbatimSite: Juan Fernandez, Isla Robinson Crusoe, V Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: The objective was to assess the reproductive biology of 25 native species of flora, including Robinsonia masafuerana and Nicotiana cordifolia native to Isla Alejandro Selkirk.  In addition, collect information on aspects related to their breeding system: pollen and ovule number, pollen/ovule ratio, pollen size, compatibility, and pollination.
Type_of_Analyses: Descriptive study. Detailed description of floral structures and of floral funciton. Pollen quantity was estimated, and ovules were counted, P/O ratio estimated. Flower visitors were assessed.

Objective_of_Article_Chapter: The objective of this experiment was determining the yield of B. napus cv. Artus pollinated by A. mellifera, under field conditions, measuring yield components such as number of seeds per silique, number of siliques per plant, 1000 grain weight and yield (t ha-1). In addition, we determined the percentage difference in rapeseed canola yield obtained by introducing bee hives into the crop field.
Type_of_Analyses: Comparison/correlation of grains per silique, silique per plant, and grain weight between treatments: total exclusion, partial exclusion, and free pollination.

dwc:reference: Arismendi et al. 2016. Molecular detection of the tracheal mite Locustacarus buchneri in native and non-native bumble bees in Chile. Insectes Sociaux, 63, 629–633. doi: 10.1007/s00040-016-0502-2
dwc:verbatimSite: Southern Chile, RM to Los Rios Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Considering the negative effects of L. buchneri tracheal mite on bees, we develop a PCR-based method for specific detection of L. buchneri from bumble bee samples, through the design specific primers based on mitochondrial DNA of the cytochrome oxidase 1 (CO1) gene for detection of L. buchneri and used them to determine the presence and the prevalence of this tracheal mite in native and non-native bumble bees in Chile.
Type_of_Analyses: A Chi-square test was run to compare the L. buchneri infestation reported on native and non-native bumble bees in Chile.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Arroyo et al. 2017. Functional role of long-lived flowers in preventing pollen limitation in a high elevation outcrossing species. AOB Plants, 9, plx050. doi: 10.1093/aobpla/plx050
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We investigated visitation rates and pollen limitation in high Andean Rhodolirium montanum. We test the hypothesis that lower visitation rates at high elevations are compensated for by the possession of long-lived flowers.
Type_of_Analyses: Visitation rates were expressed as the total number of visits per 20 min divided by the total number of flowers observed. We calculated hourly median visitation rates and temperatures 0900–1800 h. We calculated mean overall daily visitation rates and mean daily temperatures. We analysed pollen data in a non-paired design, using the seed/ovule ratio. Pollen limitation was analysed with a Zero-Inflated Negative Binomial (ZINB) model.

dwc:reference: Belmonte et al. 1994. Floral nectary structure and nectar composition in Eccremocarpus scaber (Bignoniaceae), a hummingbird-pollinated plant of central Chile. American Journal of Botany, 81(4), 493-503. doi: 10.2307/2445499
dwc:verbatimSite: Santuario de la Naturaleza Yerba Loca
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Surface features, anatomy, and ultrastructure of the floral nectary of Eccremocarpus scaber (Bignoniaceae), pollinated predominantly by the largest-knownh ummingbird (Patagona gigas gigas), were studied together  with nectar sugar content and secretion rate.
Type_of_Analyses: Descriptive study of plant morphology, key structures and nectar content and sugar ratio assessed. The low sucrose/hexose  ratio (0.25) and high nectary secretion force(nectar per flower biomass) places E. scaber close to large-bodied bat-pollinated plants.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Bernardello et al . 2000. Floral nectary structure and nectar chemical composition of some species from Robinson Crusoe Island (Chile). Canadian Journal of Botany, 78, 862-872.
dwc:verbatimSite: Juan Fernandez, Isla Robinson Crusoe, V Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Analyses of nectary structure, nectar volume and concentration, and sugar nectar chemical composition of 11 native and one adventitious species that are mainly hummingbird pollinated. Nonsugar components of the nectar were also analysed when enough nectar was available. The aim is to understand of the plant–hummingbird interactions on this island.
Type_of_Analyses: Description of nectary structures, nectar chemistry, including sugar and non-sugar components. Statistical analysis of the association between population size or pollinator type with sugar composition (eight nectar sugar traits)

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Bernardello et al. 2001. A survey of floral traits, breeding systems, floral visitors, and pollination systems of the angiosperms of the Juan Fernández Islands (Chile). The Botanical Review, 67(3), 256-308. doi: 10.1007/BF02858097
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: A species-based review of reproduction and pollination, to identify generalizations associated with these systems, to understand the evolution of these features, and to utilize these data to promote conservation. Data recorded include habit, sexual system, flower size, shape, and color, and the hypothesized pollination system of the first colonizers.
Type_of_Analyses: Results are presented as percentages. Pairwise comparisons of different features are tested for statistical association.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Bernardello et al. 2004. The reproductive biology of Sophora fernandeziana (Leguminosae), a vulnerable native species from Isla Robinson Crusoe. American Journal of Botany, 91(2), 198–206. doi: 10.3732/ajb.91.2.198
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Flowering phenology of Sophora fernandeziana, as well as floral morphology, nectar features, breeding system, and visitors were analyzed in two populations in the Juan Fernández Archipelago.
Type_of_Analyses: Nectar secretion rate (NSR) per hour was calculated dividing the amount of sugar (imm) produced by the number of hours between the measurements (mm/h). Nectar reabsorption rate (NRR) per hour was calculated by dividing the amount of sugar reabsorbed by the number of hours of the time period considered (mm/h). Pollen viability was estimated as the percentage stainability of 100 grains from each of 15 flowers using aniline blue in lactophenol.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Candia et al. 2014. Indirect positive effects of a parasitic plant on host pollination and seed dispersal. Oikos, 123, 1371-1376. doi: 10.1111/oik.01353
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We attempted to answer the following two questions: 1) are pollinator visit rate and seed rain higher in parasitized than non-parasitized R. spinosus shrubs? 2) Is recruitment around parasitized individuals higher than around non-parasitized hosts?
Type_of_Analyses: Pollination was assessed thourgh focal observations. Seed production was quantified using circular seed traps placed under R. spinosus plants. Recruitment was determined by counting number of seedlings, including degree of seedling clustering. Analyses included GLM, nbGLM and X2 goodness of fit.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Candia et al. 2014. Indirect positive effects of a parasitic plant on host pollination and seed dispersal. Oikos, 123, 1371-1376. doi: 10.1111/oik.01353

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Chalcoff et al . 2012. Erosion of a pollination mutualism along an environmental gradient in a south Andean treelet, Embothrium coccineum (Proteaceae). Oikos, 121, 471-480. doi: 10.1111/j.1600-0706.2011.19663.x
dwc:verbatimSite: Cordillera de la Costa, XIV Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We assessed whether 1) the pollinator assemblage of E. coccineum varies geographically, 2) pollination efficiency changes with assemblage composition, 3) pollen limitation increases with decreasing rainfall, and 4) observed changes in reproductive success along the gradient can be better explained by the loss  of the most effective pollinator/s than by water stress.
Type_of_Analyses: We constructed isoline maps to illustrate spatial variation in the pollinator assemblage. Using a regression approach including data from all populations, we estimated the eff ectiveness of each of the four main orders of flower visitors by relating total pollen deposition to visitation rate. We evaluated whether reproductive success decreased along the gradient of decreasing precipitation and whether any trend was associated with increasing pollen limitation.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Chetelat et al. 2009. Distribution, ecology and reproductive biology of wild tomatoes and related nightshades from the Atacama Desert region of northern Chile. Euphytica, 167, 77–93. doi: 10.1007/s10681-008-9863-6
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We summarize our observations and results from six germplasm collecting expeditions to northern Chile. The current geographic distribution, ecology, and reproductive biology of each species are described, and their future status is discussed in relation to potential impacts from human-associated activities.
Type_of_Analyses: For each population, the total number of plants in the immediate area was counted or visually estimated. To the extent possible, seed were collected from all plants bearing ripe fruit. Several fruit from each plant were harvested. A combined total of 150 individual plant collections, consisting of 92 S. chilense, 22 S. peruvianum, 21 S. lycopersicoides, and 15 S. sitiens accessions.

dwc:reference: Cisterna & Murua. 2018. Contrasting floral morphology and breeding systems in two subspecies of Calceolaria corymbosa in Central Chile. Gayana Botanica, 75(1), 544-548. doi: 10.4067/S0717-66432018000100544
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Characterize floral morphology that may be important for reproduction and assess basic aspects of reproductive biology in two subspecies of   Calceolaria corymbosa in central Chile.
Type_of_Analyses: To determine the morphological association between floral traits a Principal Component Analysis was performed. Also, in order to determine differences between subspecies the position of individuals on the axes were used to perform an ANOVA test using the subspecies factor as grouping variable.
Comments: Oil-collecting bees

Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Assess the reproductive system of  Trichopetalum plumosum (Ruiz & Pav.) J.F. Macbr. (Asparagaceae), an native geophyte of Chile.
Type_of_Analyses: We carried out five controlled pollination treatments (agamospermia, autogamia autónoma, autopolinización, polinización cruzada y natural / control).

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Diaz et al. 2005. Linking forest structure and composition: avian diversity in successional forests of Chiloe´ Island, Chile. Biological Conservation, 123, 91–101. doi: 10.1016/j.biocon.2004.10.011
dwc:verbatimSite: Senda Darwin Biological Station, Chiloe, XIV Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We show how Chilean forest bird species richness, abundance and guild structure changes as a function of structural properties of forest stands.
Type_of_Analyses: We performed a Monte–Carlo simulation on the total number of species vs. the total number of individuals observed. We evaluated whether bird species composition was nested among successional stands, by using a Nested Analysis with a T index. We compared the average species richness (number of bird species observed per point per day) among stands performing repeated measures ANOVA.

dwc:reference: Diaz Tavie et al 2015. Nuevos antecedentes acerca de la presencia de Bombus dahlbomii Geruin-Menville (Hymenoptera: Apidae) en la isla Grande de Tierra del Fuego. Anales del Instituto de la Patagonia 43:171–174.
dwc:verbatimSite: Isla Grande de Tierra del Fuego

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Estay et al. 2001b. Evaluación de Bombus dahlbomii (GUER.) como agente polinizador de flores de tomate Lycopersicon esculentum (MILL) bajo condiciones de invernadero . Agricultura Tecnica Chile, 61(2), 113-119. doi: 10.4067/S0365-28072001000200001
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Assess the native Chilean bumblebee Bombus dahlbomii (Guer) as a pollinating agent of the cultivated tomato Lycopersicon esculentum (Mill)
Type_of_Analyses: We determined the percentage yield for each treatment. We counted the number of flowers between the third and sixth cluster on 60 plants. During the harvest, the number of fruits per cluster was determined to assess yield. In addition, we randomly chose a subset of 100 fruits obtain from the third and sixth floral cluster, and on each of these we measured weight, ecuatorial radious, and number of seeds, and comparisons were assessed using a Student's t-test.

Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Summarise information from Chile, Paraguay and Peru as a contribution to the national and regional knowledge of the state of pollinators and the ecosystem service provided by pollination.
Type_of_Analyses: Richness of native species and diversity of pollinator species can represent a huge potential for these countries, and we show how in these countries pollination is becoming an important resource, relevant to agriculture. Also, this document indentifies the political, normative and administrative resources that contribute to the conservation and sustainable use of pollinators.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Farji-Brener & Corley. 1998. Successful invasions of hymenopteran insects into NW Patagonia. Ecología Austral, 8, 237-249.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We describe the successful invasion of hymenopteran insects into NW Patagonia.
Type_of_Analyses: We analyse the importance of the invading species and the characteristics of the invaded community, as well as the role of disturbance on the invasion process, by presenting the most conspicuous of the best documented case studies: the wasps Vespula germanica and Sirex noctilio, the bumblebee Bombus ruderatus, and the leaf cutting ant Acromyrmex lobicornis

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Farji-Brener & Corley. 1998. Successful invasions of hymenopteran insects into NW Patagonia. Ecología Austral, 8, 237-249.

dwc:reference: Farji-Brener & Corley. 1998. Successful invasions of hymenopteran insects into NW Patagonia. Ecología Austral, 8, 237-249.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Fonturbel et al. 2015. Scale-dependent responses of pollination and seed dispersal mutualisms in a habitat transformation scenario. Journal of Ecology, 103, 1334–1343. doi: 10.1111/1365-2745.12443
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Test the multiscale responses of pollination and seed dispersal in a habitat transformation scenario, we examined a gradient of native and transformed habitats at three spatial scales and focused on a hemiparasitic mistletoe (Tristerix corymbosus) that is almost exclusively pollinated by a hummingbird (Sephanoides sephaniodes) and dispersed by an arboreal marsupial (Dromiciops gliroides).
Type_of_Analyses: We used three analytical approaches: (i) pattern causality, (ii) pattern covariation and (iii) pattern concordance. we aimed to assess whether pollination and seed dispersal processes were covarying at the same scale and then to assess whether pollination and seed dispersal patterns were concordant in a spatially explicit scenario.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Fonturbel et al. 2017. Plant-animal mutualism effectiveness in native and transformed habitats: Assessing the coupled outcomes of pollination and seed dispersal. Perspectives in Plant Ecology, Evolution and Systematics, 28, 87-95. doi: 10.1016/j.ppees.2017.09.003
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We raise three questions: (1) does the overall effectiveness of pollination, seed dispersal and its combination change between habitats? (2) if so, are quantitative and qualitative effectiveness components of pollination and seed dispersal similarly altered? and (3) does plant reproductive outcome change between habitats?
Type_of_Analyses: For the pollinator S. sephaniodes we used the number of visitations (standardized by hour and number of flowers) as quantitative measure, and fruit set as qualitative measure. For the seed disperser D. gliroides, we used the number of visitations (standardized by hour and number of fruits) as quantitative measure, and fruit removal rates as qualitative measure.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Fonturbel et al. 2017b. Increased resource availability prevents the disruption of key ecological interactions in disturbed habitats. Ecosphere, 8(4), Article e01768. doi: 10.1002/ecs2.1768
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We studied pollination and seed dispersal rates along a habitat transformation gradient, which ranges from native forest to transformed habitats, with a large variation in structure and resource availability.
Type_of_Analyses: We fitted spatially explicit generalized additive models (GAMs), with Poisson error distribution and a log-link function.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Gomez et al . 2012. Pollination and breeding system in Adesmia bijuga Phil. (Fabaceae), a critically endangered species in Central Chile. Gayana Botanica, 69(2), 286-295. doi: 10.4067/S0717-66432012000200008
dwc:verbatimSite: Fundo San Pedro, Maule Region, VII Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We examined the pollination biology and breeding system of A. bijuga in order to explain their small number of shrubs. We estimated composition of pollinator species attracted to flowers and visitation rates.
Type_of_Analyses: We used manipulated treatments to estimate autonomous self-pollination, level of reproductive assurance and pollen limitation. The results of this study indicate that only pollinators from the order Hymenoptera visit A. bijuga.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Gonzalez et al. 2019. Is there spatial variation in phenotypic selection on floral traits in a generalist plant–pollinator system?. Evolutionary Ecology, 33, 687–700. doi: 10.1007/s10682-019-10002-7
dwc:verbatimSite: Central Chile, Jardin Botanico, V Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
(1) to describe and compare the pollinator assemblages of the ten populations under study, and (2) to determine whether there is spatial variation in the phenotypic selection on the floral traits of A. ligtu var.
simsii.
Type_of_Analyses: To determine whether pollinator assemblages of populations differ in their composition, we carried out a one-way ANOSIM using 10,000 permutations, together with pairwise a posteriori comparison. We estimated the mean number of seeds per plant as an absolute measure of female fitness (Wi). Relative female fitness per plant (wi) was estimated as the quotient between the absolute female fitness per plant and the population mean of absolute female fitness (wi = Wi/Wmean).

Type_of_Analyses: The evolutionary ecology of a mistletoe-cactus parasitism in central Chile, among others

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Guerrero et al . 2019. Bees may drive the reproduction of four sympatric cacti in a vanishing coastal mediterranean-type ecosystem. PeerJ, 7, e7865. doi: 10.7717/peerj.7865.
dwc:verbatimSite: Between Pichidangui and Los Molles, V Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We attempted to answer the following questions: (i) How similar are pollinator assemblages among sympatric cactus species? (ii) Which mating systems do sympatric cactus species use?
Type_of_Analyses: Field observations on four taxa and characterized pollinators during the years 2016 and 2017. We estimated differences in the pollinator assemblages using the Bray–Curtis index. To elucidate the mating systems, we conducted hand-pollination experiments. We tested differences in seed production for statistical significance using Kruskal–Wallis analysis.

dwc:reference: Humaña & Riveros. 1994. Biologia de la reproducción en la especie trepadora Lapageria rosea R. et P (Philesiaceae). Gayana Botanica, 51(2), 49-55.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determinar el sistema de reproducción de Lapageria rosea, y establecer el patrón fenológico. Este estudio además, se complementará con observaciones de la actividad del agente polinizador. para relacionarlo con los factores reproductivos. Además, de entregar datos sobre la asignación de biomasa en las estructuras florales y de la relación polen/óvulo.
Type_of_Analyses: Periodos de observaciones focales para determinar polinizadores, resultados presentados en porcentaje de visitas. Para la determinación de la proporción polen/ óvulos se procedió a contar los óvulos. Análisis comparativo de biomasa floral

dwc:reference: Lehnebach & Riveros. 2003. Pollination biology of the Chilean native orchid Chloraea lamellata. Biodiversity and Conservation, 12: 1741–1751. doi: 10.1023/A:1023666800948
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We present results on the reproductive biology of the native species Chl. lamellata, including aspects of the breeding system, phenology and pollinators.
Type_of_Analyses: Count of pollen grains and ovules per flower. P/O ratio was obtained following Cruden (1977).

dwc:reference: Lopez-Sepulveda et al . 2017. Biogeography and genetic consequences of anagenetic speciation of Rhaphithamnus venustus (Verbenaceae) in the Juan Fernández archipelago, Chile: insights from AFLP and SSR markers. Plant Species Biology, 32, 223–237. doi: 10.1111/1442-1984.12144.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: To interpret genetic diversity data from two types of molecular markers within the context of biological and historical factors associated with anagenetic speciation. To interpret genetic diversity and divergence in  within the context of alternative biogeographic scenarios.
Type_of_Analyses: Rercentage of polymorphic bands (PPB), total number of AFLP bands (TNB), the number of private bands (NPB) and Shannon Diversity Index (SDI). The average gene diversity over loci (AGDOL) was calculated using the program ARLEQUIN 3.5.1.2. An admixture model with correlated allele frequency (following the F-model; Falush et al 2003) was used for assigning individuals into K clusters (populations).
Comments: Artículo habla tangencialmente de la importancia de picaflores para la reproducción de esta especie, más no es un estudio directo de interacciones entre visitante floral y planta.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Magrach et al . 2012. Effects of Matrix Characteristics and Interpatch Distance on Functional Connectivity in Fragmented Temperate Rainforests. Conservation Biology, 26 (2), 238–247. doi: 10.1111/j.1523-1739.2011.01818.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We evaluated the effects of the structural connectivity of forest patches (i.e., distance between patches) and matrix class (land-cover type) on the functional connectivity of 3 bird species (the White-crested Elaenia [Elaenia albiceps], the Green-backed Firecrown Hummingbird [Sephanoides sephaniodes], and the Austral Thrush [Turdus falklandii]).
Type_of_Analyses: We fit generalized linearmixed models with a negativebinomial error distribution and a log link to the number of interpatch crosses and epiphyte fruit set and seedling and adult-plant abundance with the GLIMMIX and GENMOD procedures in SAS (version 9.1)
Comments: Turdus falklandii is not a pollinator but a seed disperser. C. valdivianum was used as a control.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Mathiasen et al . 2007. Genetic Structure and Early Effects of Inbreeding in Fragmented Temperate Forests of a Self-Incompatible Tree, Embothrium coccineum. Conservation Biology , 21 (1), 232–240. doi: 10.1111/j.1523-1739.2006.00565.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We examined the impact of forest fragmentation on genetic traits of E. coccineum. We tested the hypothesis that trees in small fragments and isolated trees are not genetically separated from the larger populations and thus experience normal or even enhanced gene flowand do not suffer frominbreeding depression.
Type_of_Analyses: A total of 406 adult trees and 432 seedlings were analyzed by protein electrophoresis. This analysis considered standard within-population parameters of genetic variation and inbreeding estimated with POPGENE,  including mean number of alleles (A); effective number of alleles (Ae); number of rare alleles (Ar); percent of polymorphic loci under the sensu stricto criterion (Pss); observed heterozygosity (Ho); and gene diversity (He).

dwc:verbatimSite: northern Chile, between the Atacama Desert and Puna
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: (1) to shed light on this species current distribution in Chile and (2) enhance the predictions of its potential range throughout the continent, in an attempt to add more information of the species distribution in South America.
Type_of_Analyses: We used species distribution models (SDMs) and multivariate analyses to evaluate whether these occurrences represent new escapes from managed colonies or natural dispersal of the species from its southern invaded range.

dwc:reference: Muñoz & Cavieres. 2019. Sharing of pollinators between the invasive Taraxacum officinale and coflowering native is not related to floral similarity in the high-Andes. Flora, 261, 151491. doi: 10.1016/j.flora.2019.151491
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: 1) assessed the degree of dependence of five cooccurring native asteraceous species on insect pollinator visitation for successful seed production, 2) determined the degree of pollinator sharing, in terms of insect species composition and percentage representation of each taxa between T. officinale and these five co-flowering species, 3) compared pollinator visitation rates and duration of visits on T. officinale to those on the five co-occurring species, and 4) assessed if there is any relationship between the degree of pollinator sharing, visitation rate and duration of visits with the similarity in floral characteristics between T. officinale and the five co-occurring native asteraceous species.
Type_of_Analyses: Pollinator visitation rates and duration of pollinator visits were expressed as mean values for each individual plant for 15-min observation periods and were compared among study species via one-way ANOVA after testing for normality and homogeneity of variances using the Shapiro-Wilks and Bartlett tests, respectively. The relationship between floral similarity and pollinator visitation patterns was assessed via Spearman rank correlations between the estimated Brays-Curtis distance between T. officinale and the native species with the Pianka’s niche overlap index.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Murua & Espindola. 2015. Pollination syndromes in a specialised plant-pollinator interaction: does floral morphology predict pollinators in Calceolaria?. Plant Biology, 17, 551–557. doi: 10.1111/plb.12225.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: (i) do morphologically different Calceolaria species interact with different pollinator groups; and (ii) is there structural covariation between floral and pollinator traits in this plant group?
Type_of_Analyses: Identify and measure the main pollinators of ten Calceolaria taxa. Later, we quantify the floral morphology of these plants and use these data to explore morphological plant–pollinator correspondence using a multivariate approach.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Murua et al. 2017. Pollinators and crossability as reproductive isolation barriers in two sympatric oil-rewarding Calceolaria (Calceolariaceae) species. Evolutionary Ecology, 31, 421-434. doi: 10.1007/s10682-017-9894-3
dwc:verbatimSite: Altos de Lircay National Reserve , VII Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: (a) we examine the strength of different reproductive barriers in the field, (b) we perform intra- and interspecific pollination crosses in the greenhouse, and (c) we examine germination of parental and hybrid seeds as a measure of offspring viability.
Type_of_Analyses: To quantify the reproductive isolation due to differences in the identity of floral visitors we used a pollinator isolation index. The effect of parental source on the mean seed production of each pollination treatment was tested using a Generalized Linear Model (GLM) with Poisson distribution and log function.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Murua et al. 2011. Changes in wing length in the pollinator Bombus dahlbomii occurring with the fragmentation of the Maulino forest, Chile. Ciencia e Investigación Agraria, 38(3), 391-396. doi: 10.4067/S0718-16202011000300008
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: To study the wing length of Bombus dahlbomii Guérin (Hymenoptera: Apidae), a native Chilean bumblebee.
Type_of_Analyses: The data were analyzed with an ANCOVA for unbalanced samples (Type IV model) with the habitat of the population as a fixed effect, the length of the wing as a response variable and the body size as a covariate.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Murua et al. 2019. Is the same pollinator species equally effective in different populations of the generalist herb Alstroemeria ligtu var. simsii?. Gayana Botanica, 76(1), 109-114. doi: 10.4067/S0717-66432019000100109
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Characterize the pollinator assemblages and determine the pollination effectiveness of the main pollinator species in three A. ligtu populations.
Type_of_Analyses: The five species with the highest visitation frequency were selected using the results of an ANOVA test. Once the main pollinator per population was identified, their pollinator effectiveness was estimated as VR*PL (Ne’eman et al 2010). Finally, to determine statistical differences in visitation rate, pollinator effectiveness and handing time of main pollinator species a GLM with Gaussian distribution was performed.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Polidori & Nieves-Andrei. 2015. Comparative flight morphology in queens of invasive and native Patagonian bumblebees (Hymenoptera: Bombus). Comptes Rendus Biologies, 338(2), 126-133. doi: 10.1016/j.crvi.2014.11.001
dwc:verbatimSite: Huinay Scientific Field Station, X Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We studied morphologies related to flight performance (flight muscle ratio (FMR), wing loading (WL), excess power index (EPI, which integrates FMR and WL) and wing aspect ratio (AR)) in the queens of the two species.
Type_of_Analyses: We performed analyses of covariance in which species, wing wear, body mass and thorax width, entered as explanatory factors. The Pearson correlation test was used to verify linear relationships between morphological parameters.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Polidori & Nieves-Andrei. 2015. Comparative flight morphology in queens of invasive and native Patagonian bumblebees (Hymenoptera: Bombus). Comptes Rendus Biologies, 338(2), 126-133. doi: 10.1016/j.crvi.2014.11.001
dwc:verbatimSite: Huinay Scientific Field Station, X Region

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Rivera-Huintel & Acevedo-Orellana. 2017. Biologia floral y reproductiva de Escallonia pulverulenta (Ruiz et Pav.) Pers. (Escalloniaceae) y su relación con los visitantes florales. Gayana Botanica, 74(1), 82-93. doi: 10.4067/S0717-66432017005000322
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determinar el sistema reproductivo, los patrones de floración, la longevidad floral y su relación con los visitantes florales de Escallonia pulverulenta.
Type_of_Analyses: Los datos fueron analizados con ANDEVA de medidas repetidas. Cuando se detectaron diferencias significativas entre tratamientos se utilizó test de Tukey como prueba de contrastes múltiples. Se utilizó test de Chi cuadrado para evaluar si la frecuencia de valores de sincronía floral observados difiere de lo esperado por el azar.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Rovere et al . 2006. Breeding system of Embothrium coccineum (Proteaceae) in two populations on different slopes of the Andes. Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 79,  225-232. doi: 10.4067/S0716-078X2006000200008
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Investigate variation of the breeding system of E. coccineum at two locations on different slopes of the Andes.  We aim to study fruit and seed production after different pollination treatments, breeding efficiency, and pollinator diversity in each population.
Type_of_Analyses: Breeding efficiency was evaluated as the ratio between the percentage of fruiting from natural pollination (uncovered flowers) to manual cross pollination (%NP / %CP). Total visits by birds and/or insects were recorded during 50 periods of 15-min. This information was compared to data gathered in Chiloe Island by a similar study (Smith-Ramírez & Armesto 2003).

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Ruz. 2002. Bee pollinators introduced to Chile. In: Pollinating Bees - The Conservation Link Between Agriculture and Nature, 155-167.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Describe and analyze the various bee species that over the years have been introduced into Chile for pollination purposes, and have colonized different geographical areas of the country, and the need for more studies to evaluate risks of foreign introductions.
Type_of_Analyses: This review concentrates on specialized literature that covers the Apis and non-Apis pollinators introduced into Chile mainly over the last 35 years.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Sanzana et al. 2012. Entomofauna polinizadora de Eucalyptus nitens en huertos semilleros del centro sur de Chile. Bosque, 33(1), 25-31. doi: 10.4067/S0717-92002012000100003
dwc:verbatimSite: Hacienda Rucamanqui de Forestal Mininco S.A., VIII Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determinar la abundancia de especies polinizadoras, asociadas al Eucalyptus nitens en un huerto semillero clonal de la hacienda Rucamanqui, localidad de Huépil (37º 15’ S y 71º 55’ O), Region del Biobío.
Type_of_Analyses: Se utilizó el coeficiente de correlación de Pearson (r) para datos paramétricos y Spearman (rs) para datos no paramétricos, que reflejaron el grado de relación lineal que existe entre cada orden de insectos con el número de flores abiertas por planta, y la temperatura ambiental. Se aplicó la prueba de t de Student para determinar las diferencias significativas entre i) el número de flores abiertas por planta y ii) la temperatura ambiental, con la frecuencia de visitas.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Schmid-Hempel. 2013. The invasion of southern South America by imported bumblebees and associated parasites. Journal of Animal Ecology, 83(4), 823-837. doi: 10.1111/1365-2656.12185
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: We report on the case of two European Bombus having been introduced for pollination in southern South America (Chile) in the 1980s and 1990s. We aimed at analysing the historical spread of these species, their population genetic structure and the presence of two common parasites, Crithidia (Trypanosomatidae) and Nosema (Microsporidia), to scrutinize the extent of the invasion and to elucidate the possible role of parasitic infections in this process.
Type_of_Analyses: We did several explicit sampling campaigns, and species distribution was analysed using spatial/GIS tools. Infections by the gut parasite, Crithidia (Trypanosomatidae), were genotyped from all host species. We checked for infection status (yes/no) with the Cyt b sequenceTo analyse the genetic data, we used GENEPOP, R-packages pegas, adegenet, hierfstat and the program STRUCTURE; for geographical rendering: R package maptool.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Smith-Ramirez et al. 2018. Las razones de por que Chile debe detener la importacion del abejorro comercial Bombus terrestris (Linnaeus) y comenzar a controlarlo. Gayana Botanica, 8(2), 118-127. doi: 10.4067/S0717-65382018000200118
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Analizar los impactos ecológicos que justifi can la prohibición de nuevos ingresos del abejorro comercial Bombus terrestris a Chile.
Type_of_Analyses: Entregamos once razones para detener los ingresos de B. terrestris a Chile y comenzar a controlarlo. Justificamos estas razones en base al trabajo realizado tanto en el país como fuera de él. Al mismo tiempo, a través de las conclusiones, mencionamos cuáles deberían ser los pasos a seguir respecto a la prohibición de ingreso de B. terrestris a Chile.

dwc:reference: Smith-Ramirez & Armesto. 2003. Foraging behaviour of bird pollinators on Embothrium coccineum (Proteaceae) trees in forest fragments and pastures in southern Chile. Austral Ecology 28, 53–60. doi: 10.1046/j.1442-9993.2003.01248.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Quantify reproductive parameters of trees (no. inflorescences per branch, total and open flowers per inflorescence) in forest fragments varying from 1 ha (small), to 20 ha (medium) and to >150 ha (large), and in remnant trees in pastures.
Type_of_Analyses: We used Pearson’s correlation to assess the relationship between bird visitation rates to flowers (pooling data for both years) and number of aggressive interactions among birds, and Spearman’s rank correlations to assess the relationship between fragment size (a categorical variable) and bird visitation rates (overall and by species) and resource supply.

dwc:verbatimEventDate: October 1999 to January 2000, October 2000 to March 2001, October 2001 to February 2002
dwc:reference: Smith-Ramirez et al. 2005. Diversity, flower visitation frequency and generalism of pollinators in temperate rain forests of Chiloe Island, Chile. Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society, 147, 399–416. doi: 10.1111/j.1095-8339.2005.00388.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: (i) assess the species richness and taxonomic composition of pollinator assemblages associated with a representative number of species of the local flora; (ii) determine the frequency of pollinator visits to each flower/plant studied; (iii) assess floral characteristics (morphology and resources) that may account for visiting patterns found among pollinators; (iv) identify potential keystone pollinators of the plant community; and (v) determine the plant species that are potential keystones for maintaining the diversity of forest pollinators.
Type_of_Analyses: Species richness of the pollinator assemblage associated with one plant species, Jaccard’s similarity index (Magurran, 1988) was calculated for all plant species pairs and a dendrogram of affinities among plant species, To test whether differences in floral morphology influenced pollinator species richness and flower visitation rates in this rain forest, we used a two-factor ANOVA.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Smith-Ramirez et al. 2014. Decadal trends in the pollinator assemblage of Eucryphia cordifolia in Chilean rainforests. Oecologia , 176, 157–169. doi: 10.1007/s00442-014-3000-0
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Assess the temporal variability of the pollinator assemblage and identified possible modulators of the observed temporal shifts.
Type_of_Analyses: Frequency data for each insect pollinator. We tested the correlations of the relative and absolute abundances of the two most common species in the pollinator assemblage (two hymenopterans) as well as their associations with the species richness and abundance of the whole set of pollinators over the 10 years of study. Correlations between the structure of the pollinator community (all of the above dependent variables) and selected climatic variables for each year, and those temperatures for the summer season only.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Suarez et al. 2004. Biologia reproductiva de Convolvulus chilensis (Convolvulaceae) en una población de Aucó (centro-norte de Chile). Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 77, 581-591. doi: 10.4067/S0716-078X2004000400001
dwc:verbatimSite: Las Chinchillas National Reserve, IV Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determinar el sistema de reproducción de C. chilensis en condiciones naturales y evaluar el efecto del tipo de polinización (autopolinización o polinización cruzada) sobre los atributos y desempeño de la progenie, a fin de detectar la posible ocurrencia de depresión por endogamia en la etapa más temprana de crecimiento.
Type_of_Analyses: Se determinó el índice de autocompatibilidad (ISI, Ruiz & Arroyo 1978) y el índice de autogamia (IAS, Ruiz & Arroyo 1978). Para la evaluación entre tratamientos de polinización de diferencias en el porcentaje de formación de frutos y el número de semillas por flor tratada se utilizó la prueba de Kruskal- Wallis.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Sun et al . 1996. Evolution of Rhaphithamnus venustus (Verbenaceae), A Gynodioecious Hummingbird-Pollinated native of the Juan Fermindez Islands, Chile. Pacific Science, 50(1), 55-65.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: (1) document differences in vegetative and floral morphology between R. spinosus and R. venustus; (2) describe differences in reproductive biology between the two species, focusing on pollination and breeding systems; (3) in the context of phylogeny, speculate on the adaptive value of morphological and reproductive changes with emphasis on floral morphology and the thorn-inflorescence complex; and (4) comment on the origin of gynodioecy in R. venustus in relation to changes in the pollination syndrome and its bearing on the evolution of gynodioecy and dioecy on oceanic islands in general.
Type_of_Analyses: Descirption of flower morphology, pollen-vvule ratio (PIO) and breeding system, pollinators, phylogeny, and microsporogenesis of this species.

dwc:reference: Valdivia & Niemeyer. 2006. Do floral syndromes predict specialisation in plant pollination systems? Assessment of diurnal and nocturnal pollination of Escallonia myrtoidea. New Zealand Journal of Botany, 44, 135-141. doi: 10.1080/0028825X.2006.9513014
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluate the relative importance of diurnal and nocturnal pollinators on the female reproductive success of E. myrtoidea.
Type_of_Analyses: To determine if E. myrtoidea is limited by pollinators for seed set, the number of seeds produced in the pollination trials of diurnaland nocturnal regimes, together with seed set in hand-pollinated flowers, were assessed by applying a one-way ANOVA followed by Tukey HSD tests for multiple comparisons.

dwc:reference: Valdivia et al. 2016. Geographic distribution and trait-mediated causes of nectar robbingby the European bumblebee Bombus terrestris on the Patagonianshrub Fuchsia magellanica. Flora, 225, 30–36. doi: 10.1016/j.flora.2016.09.010
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: The aim of this study is to evaluate the geographic distributionand causes of nectar robbing in the temperate forests of Chile, usingthe relationship between B. terrestris and F. magellanica as a study model.
Type_of_Analyses: To evaluate the effect of animal abundance on the primary nectar robbing exerted by B. terrestris onF. magellanica flowers, an ANCOVA test was performed. To evaluate the effect of floral and animal shapes on the primary nectar robbing exerted by B. terrestrison F. magellanica flowers, ANCOVA tests were performed.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Vergara et al. 2011. Are eavesdroppers multimodal? Sensory exploitation of floral signals by a non-native cockroach Blatta orientalis . Current Zoology, 57 (2), 162−174. doi: 10.1093/cz/zox050
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Study the relevance of floral scent and visual display of a night blooming, putatively hawkmoth-pollinated plant Oenothera acaulis (Onagraceae) in the attraction of non-native cockroaches Blatta orientalis (Blattodea: Blattidae), which function as facultative floral larcenists in coastal habitats of central Chile.
Type_of_Analyses: To score behaviours, we used JWatcher 10.1 software which allowed us to obtain the relative frequency and proportion of time spent on each behavioral event defined. We performed Kruskal-Wallis and post hoc Tukey tests on the combined data. Additional data were analyzed using ANCOVA with the number of conspecific roaches in the experimental array as a random factor.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Vergara et al. 2011. Are eavesdroppers multimodal? Sensory exploitation of floral signals by a non-native cockroach Blatta orientalis . Current Zoology, 57 (2), 162−174. doi: 10.1093/cz/zox050

dwc:reference: Vieli et al. 2016. Landscape effects on wild Bombus terrestris (Hymenoptera: Apidae) queens visiting highshrub blueberry fields in southcentral Chile. Apidologie , 47, 711–716. doi: 10.1007/s13592-015-0422-6
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determine pollinators visiting highshrub blueberry fields set in landscapes with differing land use pattern in south-central Chile.
Type_of_Analyses: Abundance of different pollinating insect species presented graphically. Relative abundance of pollinators related to nearby vegetation.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Wilson et al. 1994. Avian Communities of Fragmented South-Temperate Rainforests in Chile. Conservation Biology, 8(2), 508-520. doi: 10.1046/j.1523-1739.1994.08020508.x
dwc:verbatimSite: Isla Grande de Chiloe, X Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determine whether diversity and relative abundance of southtemperate rainforest birds decreased as the size of the habitat patch decreased. Ecological categories, including native, mutualists (pollinatorg seed dispersers), understory species, and species dependent on large trees.
Type_of_Analyses: Statistical comparisons used the nonparametric Kruskal-Wallis analysis of variance

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Wilson et al. 1994. Avian Communities of Fragmented South-Temperate Rainforests in Chile. Conservation Biology, 8(2), 508-520. doi: 10.1046/j.1523-1739.1994.08020508.x

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Anic et al. 2015. Number of conspecifics and reproduction in the invasive plant Eschscholzia californica (Papaveraceae): is there a pollinator mediated Allee effect?. Plant Biology, 17, 720–727. doi: 10.1111/plb.12293
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: (i) is there an Allee effect in E. californica reproduction (fruit and seed production); (ii) what is the effect of the number of E. californica individuals on the quality of seeds (mass and ermination) in conspecifics; and (iii) what is the effect of the number of E. californica individuals on pollinator visitation rate?
Type_of_Analyses: We used generalised linear models (GLM) to analyse the effect of number of conspecifics in bloom on pollinator visitation rate, seed production per fruit, fruit set, seed mass, proportion of germinated seeds, proportion of aborted seeds per fruit and post-emergent reproductive success. Variables calculated as proportions (fruit set, germination and aborted seeds per fruit) were analysed using binomial distributions of errors. We examined the relationship between spacing among individuals (CE aggregation index) in the patches and the variables pollinator visitation rate, fruit production and seed production per fruit using Spearman correlation analyses.
Comments: four 10min observation periods per hour

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Anic et al. 2015. Number of conspecifics and reproduction in the invasive plant Eschscholzia californica (Papaveraceae): is there a pollinator mediated Allee effect?. Plant Biology, 17, 720–727. doi: 10.1111/plb.12293

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Arroyo et al. 1982. Community studies in pollination ecology in the high temperate Andes of central Chile. I. Pollination mechanism and altitudinal variation. American Journal of Botany, 69(1), 82-97.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Report the pollination mechanisms and pollinators of 137 plant species (75% biotically pollinated)
Type_of_Analyses:
The study area was devided according to altitude: 2200-2600, 2700-3100 y 3200-3600. Forcal observations in each altitudinal range to identify pollinators and calculate visitation rate. 
Pollination potential of each visitor was assessed.

Display size preferences and foraging habits of high andean butterflies pollinating Chaetanthera lycopodioides (Asteraceae) in the subnival of the central Chilean Andes. Arctic, Antarctic and Alpine Research, 39(3), 347-352. doi: 10.1657/1523-0430(06-017)[ARROYO]2.0.CO;2
dwc:verbatimSite: Cerro Tres Puntas, La Parva - Valle Nevado
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar si las mariposas que visitan a Chaetanthera lycopodioides a 3450 msnm prefieren display florales grandes.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Se marcó un plot en cada sitio para realizar observaciones focales de mariposas. 
2-. Se identificaron las mariposas y se registró el tamaño del display floral de cada planta. Además se registró la duración de la secuencia de visitas de una mariposa dentro del plot. 
3-. Cada día se registró el número de flores abiertas en el plot y la Tº del aire a 1, 50 y 150 cm sobre el suelo cada 30 min.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Botto-Mahan & Ojeda-Camacho. 2000. The importance of floral damage for pollinator visitation in Alstroemeria ligtu L.. Revista Chilena de Entomologia, 26: 73-76.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
Evaluar el efecto de daño floral artificial en A.ligtu sobre 
la tasas de visita de polinizadores.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Seleccionaron 7 parches en el sitio que tuvieran carateristicas bióticas y abióticas similares. 
2-. Seleccionaron y marcaron un total de 108 flores focales y recibieron 1 de los 6 tratamientos usados: 1) daño asimétrico 10%, 2) daño simétrico 10% (1 y 2 tienen 10% de daño en los pétalos laterales), 3) daño simétrico 20%, 4) daño asimétrico 20% (3 y 4 tienen 20% de daño en los pétalos laterales), 5) remoción completa de los pétalos amarillos con guías de nectar, 6) control: flores no dañadas.
3-. Observaciones focales en cada una de las flores focales marcadas. Indentificación de visitantes y registro de la duración de la visita. 
4-. Determinación de la exportación de polen. Se capturaron 4 especies de polinizador y se examinó el contenido de polen bajo microscopio.

Type_of_Analyses:

2.- Evaluación de la reflectancia de la guía de néctar

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Botto-Mahan et al . 2011. Floral herbivory affects female reproductive success and pollinator visitation in the perennial herb Alstroemeria ligtu (Altroemeriaceae). International Journal of Plant Science, 172(9), 1130-1136. doi: 10.1086/662029
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Examinar la importancia de las guías de néctar en la atracción a polinizadores y el éxito reproductivo de A.ligtu spp. simsii.
Type_of_Analyses:
1-. Estimar del grado de herbivoría floral. En 100 plantas se registró el nº de flores dañadas, tipo de pétalo que se encuntraba dañado y el grado de daño. 
2-. Indentificación de los herbivoros florales. 
3-. Examinar si el color reflectado por las guías de nectar difería del reflectado por los otros pétalos.
4-. Examinar el grado de variación en los colores del tépalo lateral y la guía de néctar. Para eso, se estimó la similitud perceptual del color del tépalo usando el modelo de receptor de ruido limitado (RNL model) de la visión del color de abejas. 
5-. Procemiento experimental para evaluar el efecto de la remosión de las guías de néctar en las tasas de visita y el éxito reproductivo. Se realizaron 3 tratamientos: remosión de los tépalos con guías de nectar, remosión de los tépalos laterales y control sin daño. Se registro la identidad y la tasas de visita de los polinizadores, tiempo de manipulación, set de frutos, número de semillas producidas y viabilidad de las semillas.  
6-. Con la información de los polinizadores se calculó: Riqueza de especies y índoce de Shannon-Wiener.
7-. Como material anexo agregan información de biología reproductiva. 4 tratamientos: autopolinización automática, polinizaciñon cruzada manual, flores emasculadas y control.

Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar el efecto del robo de nectar y la polinización (diseño 2x2) en distintas medidas de fitness en el muerdago Tristerix aphyllus.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Efecto del robo de nectar (hormigas) y la polinización (picaflores) sobre el set de frutos, germinación, peso semillas, disponibilidad de néctar.
2.- Efecto del robo de nectar sobre la tasa y tiempo de visitas.
3.- Proporción de plantas robadas y no robadas

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Carvallo & Medel. 2005. The modular structure of the floral phenotype in Mimulus luteus var. luteus (Phrymaceae). Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 78(4), 665-672. doi: 10.4067/S0716-078X2005000400006
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Describe the interdependence of nine floral traits in the herb Mimulus luteus var. luteus (Phrymaceae), as an attempt to characterize functional modules on which natural selection can potentially act upon.
Type_of_Analyses: Morphological measurements were recorded from two sets of digital pictures on each corolla. We recorded corolla size (CS), nectar guide size (NGS), anther height (AH), and stigma aperture angle (AA). To explore patterns of trait covariation, we used the notion of conditional independence developed by Magwene (2001). We constructed a simple correlation matrix among all variables.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Carvallo & Medel. 2010. Effects of herkogamy and inbreeding on the mating system of Mimulus luteus in the absence of pollinators. Evolutionary Ecology, 24(2), 509-522. doi: 10.1007/s10682-009-9322-4
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar el ambiente de polinización, niveles de depresión por endogamia y hercogamia en M. luteus para determinar en que medidas estos factores determinan los niveles de autogamia en la población.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Determinar si existen diferencias en hercogamia de movimiento y producción de semillas en plantas con auto-polinización, polinización cruzada y control.
2.- Depresión por endogamia (en terminos de producción y germinación de semillas). 
3.-  Análisis de selección en flores abiertas y embolsadas. Rasgo: hercogamia (distancia antera-estigma) y largo del tubo, medida de fitness: producción de semillas.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Carvallo et al. 2013. Assessing the effects of native plants on the pollination of an exotic herb, the blueweed Echium vulgare. Arthropod-Plant Interactions, 7(5), 475-484. doi: 10.1007/s11829-013-9265-0
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluación del efecto de las plantas natives (Schizanthus hookeri y Stachys albicaulis) sobre la polinización de la especie exótica Echium vulgare.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Determinar si existen diferencias en riqueza y diversidad de visitantes en parches mixtos (native + E. vulgare) 
y parches monoespecíficos. 
2.- Calculo de dos índices de similitud en la composición de visitante: Sørensen y Bray–Curtis
3.- Determinar el efecto del tipo de parche (mixto o monoespecífico) en el set de frutos y la razón semilla:ovulo para cada una de las especies de planta.
Comments:
Estudiaron 7 parches. 5 de ellos monoespecíficos y 2 eran una mezcla de 
E.vulgare con una native.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Cavieres et al . 1998. Efecto del tamaño floral y densidad de flores en la visita de insectos polinizadores en Alstroemeria pallida Graham (Amaryllidaceae). Gayana Botánica, 55(1), 1-10.
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar el efecto del tamaño de las flores, bajo condiciones de alta y baja densidad de flores, en el número de visitas de insectos polinizadores en A. pallida
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Manipulación de la densidad de flores para evaluar su efecto sobre las visitas. Se redujo manualmente el número de flores en una parcela hasta dejar 1 flor/m2 y otra parcela con la densidad natural de flores (2 flores/m2). A su vez, cada parcela fue subdividida en 2. En una de las subparcelas por parcela se cortaron lo pétalos a la mitad.
2.- Observaciones focales en las parcelas. Se registró el número y tipo (visita flores entre individuos o del mismo ind.) de visita y indentificación de especies.  Con esta información se calcularon tasas de visita y se calculó la probabilidad de que una flor sea visitada durante el período de observación.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Celedón-Neghme et al. 2007. Cost and benefits of attractive floral traits in the annual species Madia sativa (Asteraceae). Evolutionary Ecology, 21(2), 247-257. doi: 10.1007/s10682-006-9002-6
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar los costos y beneficios asociados con los rasgos de atracción en Madia sativa.
Type_of_Analyses:
1-. Trabajaron con 12 plots donde estimaron al densidad de plantas por plot. En 15 flores por plot midieron: nº de capítulos abiertos, nº de "ray florets" por capítulo y altura planta. 
2-. En las mismas 15 plantas por plot realizaron observaciones focales estimando tasas y tiempo de las visitas. Usaron regresión logística para ver relación entre tasas de visita y las veriables medidas en el punto 1. 
3-. Evaluación de los costos asociados a los ray florets en ausencia de polinizadores. Seleccionaron 36 plantas y 2 brotes de cada planta. Excluyeron a los polinizadores de visitar uno de los brotes y el otro quedó como control. Al comienzo de la antesis contaron el nº de ray florets. Al final de la temporada registraron: razón semilla: óvulo, peso semillas, germinación de semilla y razón semilla:florets. Los datos fueron analizados usando ANCOVA. Para la germinación se usó la prueba de pares emparejados de Wilcoxon.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Cooley et al. 2008. Is floral diversification associated with pollinator divergence? flower shape, flower colour and pollinator preference in Chilean Mimulus. Annals of Botany, 101(5), 641-650. doi: 10.1093/aob/mcn014
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
Evaluar si la variación floral en 4 especies de Mimulus 
está asociada con la variación en los polinizadores.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Estudiar diferencias entre Especies, poblaciones y familias (en invernadero) para los rasgos: volumen y concentración néctar, altura estigma, distancia antera-estigma, largo corola, altura máxima tubo, ancho máximo garganta, patrones UV y pigmentos.
2.- En 4 de las 6 poblaciones se evaluaron tasas de visita y tiempos de cierre de estigmas en terreno.
3.- Análisis de correspondencia canónica para ver en que medida los rasgo flores medidos permiten diferenciar las especies.
4.- Solo para la población de Rio Tinguiririca se evaluó la conducta el polinizador B.dahlbomii en los híbridos.
Comments:
Se tomaron frutos de cada una de las poblaciones y se crecieron plantas en el
 invernadero (10 familias por población).

dwc:reference: Cuartas-Dominguez & Medel. 2010. Pollinator-mediated selection and experimental manipulation of the flower phenotype in Chloraea bletioides. Functional Ecology, 25(6), 1219-1227. doi: 10.1111/j.1365-2435.2010.01737.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
Cuantificar la selección medida por polinizadores sobre 
rasgos morfológicos en Chloraea bletioides.
Type_of_Analyses: 1.- Análisis de selección: Rasgos estudio observacional: Ancho flor, largo flor, área lebelo, largo tubo floral, altura planta y nº flores. Rasgos estudio manipulativo: corte en los sepalos laterales y en el labelo. Medidas de fitness: Nº polinias removidas y nº de frutos producidos.
Comments: Hicieron un estudio experimetal y uno manipulativo de selección.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Espinoza et al. 2012. Reproductive consequences of flower damage in  two contrasting habitats:The case of Viola portalesia (Violaceae) in Chile. Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 85(4), 503-511. doi: 10.4067/S0716-078X2012000400012
dwc:verbatimSite: Los Ruiles National Reserve, VII Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar el efecto de la herbivoría floral sobre la producción de semillas de V.portalesia en dos ambientes contrastantes (native e intervenido).
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Efecto de remoción artificial (Manipulativo: remoción pétalo de aterrizaje, remoción pétalos inferiores, remoción pétalos superiores, control sin daño) en la producción de semillas usando el nº de flores como covariable. 
2.- Frecuencia herbivoría natural.
3.- Riqueza ensambles y tasas de visita.
4.- Comparación entre sitios.
Comments: Proponene que cambos en el ensamble por modificaciones del hábitat pueden alterar el impacto de la florivoría sobre el fitness de las plantas.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference:
Galetto et al . 1998. The relationship between floral nectar 
composition and visitors in Lycium (Solanaceae) from Argentina and Chile: What does it reflect?. Flora, 193(3), 303-314. doi: 10.1016/S0367-2530(17)30851-4
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determinar si la composición química del néctar está correlacionada con la forma floral y los polinizadores o si es un rasgo conservado.
Type_of_Analyses:
1-. Medición de rasgos: Volumen y concetración de néctar, análisis cromatográfico de azucares, razón de azucares (sucrosa/fructosa+glucoa), razón de hexosa (glucosa/fructosa).
2-. En plantas con abundante nectar, se evaluó contenido de aminoacidos, lipidos, fenoles, alcaloides y ácidos reducidos. 
3-. Estudio de la morfología floral
4-. Observación de polinizadores para su identificación
Comments:
Se evaluaron 54 poblaciones en Chile y Argentina. Solo 5 poblaciones en Chile. 
Para las dos variedades de L. chilense se estudiaron sitios en Chile y Argentina. Para L.rachidocladum solo 1 sitio en Chile. Los polinizadores visitantes están definidos por especie en el articulo por lo que abarcan todos los ditios medidos. Es por esto que en esta planilla solo se reporta el número de especies polinizadoras para la especie L.rachidocladum.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Gonzalez et al. 2014. Temporal and spatial variation of the pollinator  assemblages in Alstroemeria ligtu (Alstroemeriaceae). Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 85(7). doi: 10.1186/0717-6317-87-5
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Estudiar la variación temporal y espacial del ensamble de polinizadores de A.ligtu.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Marcaron 74-200 plantas por población y caracterizaron el ensamble de polinizadores en términos de diversidad y abundancia. 
2.- Observaciones focales para registrar la frecuencia de polinización y cálculo de tasas de visita. 
3.- Comparación de la similitud de los ensambles de polinizadores usando análsis de clusters en PAST.
4.- Correlación entre las matrices de composición de polinizadores de los dos años estudiados usando un test de Mantel.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Gonzalez et al. 2015. Floral integration and pollinator diversity in the generalized plant-pollinator system of Alstroemeria ligtu (Alstroemeriaceae). Evolutionary Ecology, 21(9), 63-75. doi: 10.1007/s10682-014-9746-3
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Estimar los niveles de integración floral en 10 poblaciones de A.ligtu y ver si existe alguna relación con los ensambles de polinizadores, clima o distancia geográfica.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Estimación de la integración floral en las distintas poblaciones. Rasgos usados: tépalo apical, tépalo con guía de nectar, tepalo lateral, tépalo basal.
2.- Diversidad y Composición de los ensambles de polinizadores en cada población.
3.- Ínidce de similitud de ensambles (por par de poblaciones).
4.- Relación entre la integración floral, el clima y la distancia geográfica de las poblaciones.
5.- Relación entre la integración floral y los polinizadores.
Comments: Buscaron relaciones correlacionales entre intergración, varibales climáticas, rasgos del polinizador más importante y distancia geográfica

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Gonzalez-Gomez &  Valdivia. 2005. Direct and indirect effects of nectar robbing on the pollinating behavior of Patagona gigas (Trochilidae). Biotropica, 37(4), 693-696. doi: 10.1111/j.1744-7429.2005.00088.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar los efectos directos e indirectos (vía cambios en la conducta del polinizador) del robo de nectar sobre el éxito resproductivo de P.coerulea.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Evaluar el efecto del robo de nectar ( 3 tratamientos : Flores no dañadas, Flores con el perianto perforado, Flores con el perianto destruído) sobre:  producción de néctar (volumen), proporción de flores sin néctar,volumen cosechado de néctar, concentración de azucar en el néctar (standing crop).
2.- Registro del nº de flores con las estructuras reproductivas dañadas. 
3.- Tasas de visita en flores con distinta proporción de robo.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Humaña et al. 2008. Breeding system and pollination of selected orchids of the genus Chloraea (Orchidaceae) from central Chile. Flora, 203(6), 469-473. doi: 10.1016/j.flora.2007.08.004
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Estudiar las biología reproductiva y polinización en un grupo de especies de género Chloraea en chile central.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- 4 tratamientos más un control con polinización natural para evaluar biología reproductiva para cada especie en los dos sitios:
- Embolsar flores emasculadas (Prueba de apomixis) 
- Embolsas flores intactas (Prueba de autopolinización automática) 
- Embolsar flores emasculadas y polinizadas manualmente con polen de la misma planta  ( Pueba de geitonogamia)
- Embolsar flores emasculas y polinizadas manualmente con polen de otras plantas (Prueba de xenogamia) 
2.- Cálculo de índice de auto-incompatibilidad
6.- Tasas de visitas para 1 temporada por especie.
Comments:
Una de las poblaciones que usaron para otra especie del mismo género queda 
fuera del rango (38 S)

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Ladd & Arroyo. 2009. Comparisons of breeding systems between two sympatric species, Nastanthus spathulatus (Calyceraceae) and Rhodophiala rhodolirion (Amaryllidaceae), in the high Andes of central Chile. Plant Science Biology, 24(1), 2-10. doi: 10.1111/j.1442-1984.2009.00234.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
Estudiar las caraterísticas reproductivas de dos especies 
en simpatria.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Evaluación de la densidad de plantas.
2.- Tasas de visitas y tiempo de visitas.
3.- Solo para Rhodophiala, se examino la carga y localización de polen en las especies visitantes.
4.- Tratamientos biología reproductiva: 
- Nastanthus: Polinización natural, polinización natural con polinización cruzada artificial, autopolinización espontanea, polinización por viento en flores emasculadas y cubiertas con una malla, polinización por viento en flores cubiertas con una malla sin emascular. 
- Rhodophiala: Polinización natural, polinización natural con polinización cruzada artificial, stigma clogging: primer día autopolinización manual y 1-2 días después polinización manual cruzada, autopolinización espontanea, autopolinización manual, polinización manual en flores emasculadas. 
5.- Determinación de la cantidad de polen en los estigmas.
Comments: Para N.spathulatus no registraron visitante, pero proponen que unas abejas pequeñas (andrénidos) podrían ser las responsables de la polinización.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference:
Lander et al. 2009. Flower and fruit production and insect
 pollination of the endangered Chilean tree, Gomortega keule in native forest, exotic pine plantation and agricultural environments. Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 82(3), 403-412. doi: 10.4067/S0716-078X2009000300007
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determinar si los patrones de floración y formación de G. keule difieren entre zonas con plantación de pino, cultivateds y con bosque native.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Determinar si existen diferencias en rasgos asociados a la floración y fructificación en 2 zonas distintas 
(cultivated y bosque native):
- Estatus de floración en un tiempo determinado (sin flores, 1-10 flores, 11-100 flores, más de 100)
- Presencia/ausencia de frutos.
2.- Captura de insectos visitantes. Se realizó en 7 árboles pertenencientes a 5 sitios. 4 árboles en bosque native y 3 en zona agricola. Los insectos fueron identificados y se cuantificó la cantidad de polen que acarreaban. Se registraron y capturaron insectos que se encontraban entre 1 y 5 m sobre el suelo y los que visitaban las flores.
Comments:
Los sitios correspondientes a plantación de pino fueron excluídos de los análisis debido a la baja floración y fructificación.
Solo se anotaron las coordenadas de los sitios donde se capturaron insectos ya que las otras coordenadas no estaban disponibles. En total se estudiaron 26 sitios entre la VII y la VII Region.

dwc:reference: Medel et al. 2003. Pollinator-mediated selection on the nectar  guide phenotype in the Andean Monkey flower, Mimulus luteus. . Ecology, 84(7), 1721-1732. doi: 10.1890/01-0688
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
Estudiar la selección mediada por polinizadores sobre la 
guía de néctar
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Evaluar la importancia de la guía de néctar como indicador de la disponibilidad de nectar (se midió volumen y concentración de nectar para ver su relación con el tamaño de la guía de nectar, usando el tamaño de la flor como co-variable)
2.- Tasas de visita 
3.- Determinación de preferencias de los polinizadores en términos de tamaño de corola y guía y forma de la guía. Durante las observaciones folcales se fotografiaron las flores visitas registrando a qué polinizador correspondían. 
4.- Evaluación de la sobreposición en los tiempos de visita de las distintas especies.
5.- Cálculo de coeficiente de selección usando como rasgos: tamaño de la corola y la guía, forma de la guía y altura de la planta y como medida de fitness: número de semillas.

Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar la variación geográfica del tamaño de la carola y la guía y los ensambles de polinizadores en 7 poblaciones de M.luteus

1.- Caracterización del fenotipo floral de cada población: Tamaño de la corola y la guía.

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Molina-Montenegro et al. 2008. Positive interactions among plant species for pollinator service: assessing the ‘magnet species’ concept with invasive species. Oikos, 117(12), 1833-1839. doi: 10.1111/j.0030-1299.2008.16896.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
Comprobar la hipotesis que indica que Lupinus arboreus 
actua como una especie imán para Carduus pycnocephalus.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Comparación de las tasas de visita de individuos de C. pycnocephalus creciendo solos y individuos creciendo asociados a L. arboreus (a menos de 0,2 m). Para esto se hicieron observaciones focales para el cardo en plots son y sin L. arboreus. Se registró el número de visitantes por plot por individuo y se calcularon tasas de visita que fueron comapradas usando ANOVA de medidas repetidas.
2.- Evaluación del efecto de la densidad de plantas en las tasas de visita medidas en el punto anterior. Se realizaron más tasas de visita en un segundo año de mediciones (4 años después) en plot con densidad de Cardo baja, media y alta en asociación con L. arboreus y solos. Los datos fueron analizados usando ANCOVA con la densidad de flores como covariable.
3-. Evaluación del efecto de las asociación entre las dos especies en la producción de semillas. Se seleccionaron 25 ind creciendo solos y 25 asociados a L. arboreus (3 capítulos por planta). La producción de semillas se calculó como la razón entre el nº de semillas llenas y el total de semillas producidas. Se usaron los promedios por planta y se usó t student para las comparaciones.
4-. Evaluación de la disponibilidad de nitrógeno en el entorno de las raices del cardo. Se tomaron muestra de suelo de 5 ind solos y de 5 asociados en 2 años en las que se evaluó la concentración de amonicao y nitrato.  Analisis con ANOVA de dos vías.
5-. Evaluación de la disponibilidad de agua se realizó en 10 cardos por tratameinto para los 2 años y se midió el potencial hídrico mátrico. Analisis con ANOVA de dos vías

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Muñoz & Arroyo. 2004. Negative impacts of a vertebrate predator on insect pollinator visitation and seed output in Chuquiraga oppositifolia, a high Andean shrub. Oecologia, 138(1), 66-73. doi: 10.1007/s00442-003-1405-2
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Evaluar la hipotesis que indica que la presencia de lagartijas y aves insectivoras pueden tener un efecto negativo en la producción de semillas en C. oppositifolia por una reducción en las visitas por polinizadores.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Se realizó un diseño factorial 2x2 con exclusiones de lagartijas y aves insectívoras como tratamientos y se evaluó su efecto sobre tasas de visita, tiempo de visitas y producción de semillas.
2.- Experimento natural. Eligieron arvustos cercanos y lejanos a rocas y compararon tasas de visitas, duración de las visitas y producción de semillas.

dwc:verbatimEventDate: December 2005 to March 2005; December 2005 to March 2006
dwc:reference: Muñoz & Cavieres . 2008. The presence of a showy invasive plant disrupts  pollinator service and reproductive output in native alpine species only at high densities. Journal of Ecology, 96(3), 459-467. doi: 10.1111/j.1365-2745.2008.01361.x
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
Evaluar el efecto de la presencia de una planta 
introduced sobre dos especies natives.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Evaluar en que grado las especies comparten polinizadores y comparación de los patrones de visitas a las 
distintas especies de planta (identificación polinizadores, porcentaje de representación, tasas de visita y tiempo de visitas). Para calcular el grado de similitud se usó el índice de sobreposición de nicho de Pianka (1973) (año 1)
2.- Evaluar la dependencia de las especies natives a los polinizadores en terminos de producción de semillas usando un experimento manipulativo de exclusión de polinizadores. (año 1)
3.- Evaluación del grado de limitación de polen en presencia y ausencia de T. officinale (Experimeto factorial 2X2 con polinización natural/suplemento manual y presencia/ausencia de T.officinale). (año2)
4.- Evaluar el impacto de T. officinale a dos densidades diferentes (1 individuo o 5 individuos) en las visitas de los polinizadores y la producción de semillas. (año 2)

dwc:reference: Muñoz et al. 2005. Bottom-up effects of nutrient availability on flower production, pollinator visitation, and seed output in a high-Andean shrub. Oecologia, 143(1), 126-135. doi: 10.1007/s00442-004-1780-3
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Determinar el efecto de la disponibilidad de nutrientes sobre la producción de flores, tasas de visita y producción de semillas
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Experimeto manipulativo para evaluar el efecto de agregar Nitrógeno en C.oppositifolia. Dos niveles del 
tratamiento : control y nitrógeno. Se usaron como variables respuesta: número y tamaño de las inflorescencias, tasas de visita, duración de las visitas, producción de semillas, tamaño y viabilidad de las semillas y crecimiento vegetativo (variables medidas al 1er y 3er año luego de la suplementación).

dc:creator: Giselle Muschett
dwc:reference: Murua et al . 2010. Does human-induced habitat transformation modify pollinator-mediated selection? A case study in Viola portalesia (Violaceae). Oecologia, 163(1), 153-162. doi: 10.1007/s00442-010-1587-3
Objective_of_Article_Chapter: Estudio sobre el efecto de la transformación del habitat inducida por el hombre sobre la selección mediada por polinizadores
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Observaciones focales para registro de polinizadores y sus visitas. 
2.- Cálculo de índice de similitud de ensambles en las pobalciones (hábitat native vs transformado).
3.- Análisis morfométrico. Rasgos medidos: Altura planta, número de flores por planta, largo y ancho de la flor, forma de la flor (análisis de morfometría geométrica).
4.- Análisis de selección fenotípica. Rasgos evaluados: los mismo que en el análisis morfométrico. Medida de Fitness: producción de semillas promedio por planta. 
5.- Comparación de los coeficientes de selección entre poblaciones usando ANCOVA.
Comments: Se estudió un hábitat native y otro transformado

dwc:reference: Murua et al . 2014. Pollination ecology and breeding system of two Calceolaria species in Chile. Revista Chilena de Historia Natural, 81(7). doi: 10.1186/0717-6317-87-7
dwc:verbatimSite: Altos de Lircay National Reserve, VII Region
Objective_of_Article_Chapter:
Estudio sobre polinización y biología reproductiva en dos 
especies del género Calceolaria.
Type_of_Analyses:
1.- Determinación del sistema de apareamiento. Se realizaron 4 tratamientos: control, polinización cruzada manual, 
polinización automática (flores intactas embolsadas) y auto-polinización manual.
2.- Cálculo del índice de autoincompatibilidad y del índice de autogamia. 
3.- Observaciones focales para identificar polinizadores y cuantificar sus visitas.
Comments:
Las especie en estudio habitan en simpatría en la reserva y están distribuidas 
en parches monoespecíficos.
